Value Count Summary (Job Listings Dataset)¶

job_id¶

  • A unique numerical identifier assigned to each job listing.

  • Example: 7.012301e+10

job_role¶

  • The title of the job position being offered.

  • Examples: Branch Banking - Calling For Women Candidates, Product Owner Senior Manager, SAP BO Consultant.

company¶

  • The name of the employer or the organization that has posted the job.

  • Examples: Hdfc Bank, Accenture, Mindtree.

experience¶

  • required level of professional experience, typically listed in a range of years.

  • Examples: 1-6 Yrs, 11-15 Yrs.

salary¶

  • Indicates the compensation for the role. In many cases, this information is not publicly shared.

  • Example: Not disclosed.

location¶

  • The geographical location(s) where the job is based. It can include multiple cities or specify work arrangements like 'Hybrid'.

  • Examples: Kolkata, Hyderabad/Secunderabad, Pune, Ahmedab..., Hybrid - Kolkata, Hyderabad/Secunderabad, Pune...

rating¶

  • The overall rating of the company, likely sourced from employee feedback on a scale of 1 to 5.

  • Example: 4.0, 4.1.

reviews¶

  • The total number of reviews the company has received on the job portal.

  • Example: 39110 Reviews, 32129 Reviews.

responsibilities¶

  • A summary of the key skills, qualifications, or duties required for the job. The data shows this as a comma-separated list.

  • Examples: Customer Service,Sales,Relationship Management, SAP BO,PL / SQL,Oracle SQL,SAP Business Object....

posted_on¶

  • Indicates how recently the job advertisement was published.

  • Example: 1 Day Ago.

job_link¶

  • A direct URL link to the detailed job description on the original job website (e.g., naukri.com).

company_link¶

  • A URL link to the company's profile or careers page on the job website.

Observation¶

  • The job role column has significant inconsistencies because different organizations use varying titles for the same position. For example, a role like a Power BI Analyst might be listed as "Power BI," "BI Analyst," or "BI developer" by different companies.

  • Although the responsibilities of these roles are identical, the different names make them appear as unique job titles in the dataset. This inflates the number of distinct job roles to nearly 50,000, which does not accurately reflect the actual number of unique jobs in the market. This issue occurs because organizations often use their own naming conventions, adding terms like "Associate" or "Trainee" to a job title.

  • Manually cleaning and standardizing this column would be a massive undertaking. Therefore, an automated solution, such as using a Large Language Model (LLM), would be necessary to group these similar titles. Without such tools, the column might have to be left as is.

Observations on Company Ratings¶

  • A vast majority of the job listings are from companies with good to excellent ratings. The most common ratings cluster is between 3.9 and 4.2, which together account for over half of all the jobs listed.

  • The single most frequent rating is 4.1, appearing in nearly 8,000 job posts. This suggests that a large number of established and well-regarded companies are actively hiring.

  • Interestingly, over 1,200 listings are from companies with a perfect 5.0 rating. This could point to newer companies that have only accumulated positive reviews or exceptionally well-managed organizations.

  • There is a noticeable lack of companies with low ratings (below 3.5). This implies that either companies with poor reputations post fewer jobs on the platform or that the dataset primarily reflects jobs at more reputable firms.

Observations on Company Reviews¶

  • Dominated by Large Corporations: The data is heavily skewed by a few very large companies. The most common review counts, 32,129 and 32,151, appear thousands of times. This strongly suggests they belong to one or two major corporations (like Accenture or TCS) that have posted a massive number of job openings.

  • A Tale of Two Extremes: The job market represented here is highly polarized. On one side, you have established giants with tens of thousands of reviews. On the other, there's a significant number of companies with very few reviews, like 2 or 3.

  • Presence of New or Small Companies: There are over 2,500 job listings from companies with just 2 or 3 reviews. This highlights a large and active market of startups, small businesses, or companies that are new to the platform and are also hiring aggressively.

Observations on Job Responsibilities¶

  • Insurance & BFSI Sector Dominance: The most common job responsibilities are overwhelmingly concentrated in the Insurance and BFSI (Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance) sectors. Keywords like Life Insurance, agency, advisors, and bfsi are extremely prevalent.

  • Focus on Sales Channel Management: A vast number of these roles are centered around sales channel management. This involves managing different ways insurance products are sold, such as the tied channel (agents who work exclusively for one company), agency channel (a network of agents), direct sales, and Bancassurance (selling insurance through bank branches).

  • High Demand for Managers and Trainers: The data highlights a strong demand for individuals with leadership and development skills. Phrases like team handling, Team Management, training, and learning & development appear in nearly every popular skill set, indicating these roles are often for managers or team leaders responsible for a sales force. 📈

  • The dataset contains two main data types: float64 (for numerical data) and object (for text or mixed data).

Numerical Columns (float64)¶

  • These columns contain numeric data. float64 is a type that can hold numbers with decimal points.

  • job_id: A unique numerical identifier for each job listing.

  • rating: The numerical rating of the company, likely on a 1-5 scale. This column has a significant number of missing values.

Categorical & Text Columns (object)¶

In the context of a pandas DataFrame, the object data type is a general category used to store text data (strings). It can sometimes also hold mixed data types.

  • job_role: The title of the job (e.g., "Data Scientist").

  • company: The name of the hiring company.

  • experience: The required years of experience (e.g., "1-6 Yrs").

  • salary: The salary information, which is often text like "Not disclosed".

  • location: The city or region where the job is located.

  • reviews: The number of company reviews, stored as text (e.g., "39110 Reviews").

  • resposibilities: A text description of the job's key skills and duties. (Note: There is a typo in the column name; it should be "responsibilities".)

  • posted_on: The date or relative time the job was posted (e.g., "1 Day Ago").

  • job_link: A URL string linking to the job posting.

  • company_link: A URL string linking to the company's profile.

Checking For Duplicates¶

df.duplicated().sum()
Out[23]:

Detecting Outliers in the Dataset¶

  • The IQR (Interquartile Range) method was used to detect outliers in all numerical columns as part of the non-visual analysis.

Steps:¶

  • Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
  • Compute IQR = Q3 - Q1
  • Define lower and upper bounds:
  • Lower bound = Q1 − 1.5 × IQR
  • Upper bound = Q3 + 1.5 × IQR
  • Any value outside this range is considered an outlier
  • But there is no need of identify the outliers in my dataset because the rating column is range from 0-5 the is no record that have rating greater then 5 and less then 0.
  • We got this from value_counts itself only

Conclusion¶

During the exploratory data analysis, we familiarized ourselves with the dataset. We identified all the columns, determined their respective data types, and examined the value counts for each one. We also found that several columns contain null values, which will be addressed during the data cleaning phase.

Next, we identified duplicate rows in the data. These will be removed to ensure data consistency. We also searched for outliers, focusing on the two numerical columns: job_id and rating. Since job_id is a unique identifier, outlier analysis is not applicable to it. For the rating column, the value counts confirmed that all ratings fall within the expected 0 to 5 range, so there are no outliers present in this column either.

This completes our data exploration. Now that we understand the data's structure, types, and issues, we can proceed with the data cleaning process.

What this does:¶

  • Remove " PA." suffix (stands for "Per Annum")
  • Remove commas from numbers (e.g., "5,00,000" → "500000")
  • Split by hyphen to handle salary ranges (e.g., "300000-500000")
  • Take first part [0] as minimum salary
  • Strip whitespace for clean data

Example transformations:¶

"3,00,000 - 5,00,000 PA." → "300000"

"2,50,000 PA." → "250000"

Categories of removed data:¶

  • Educational Qualifications: "MBA/PGDM", "B.Tech/B.E.", "MBBS"
  • Vague Salary Ranges: "Less than 50000", "9.5 Cr and above"
  • Mixed Education-Salary Text: "CA MBA/PGDM M.Com B.Com"
  • Invalid Entries: Non-numeric values

Why remove these?¶

  • They don't represent actual salary figures
  • They would corrupt numerical analysis
  • They appear to be data entry errors or misplaced information

Observation¶

  • The dataset contains a total of 72,954 job records, and these jobs are from 15,295 unique companies.

What This Means¶

  • The key insight is that the number of jobs is much larger than the number of unique companies. This indicates that many companies have posted multiple jobs in this dataset.

  • On average, each company has listed approximately 4.8 jobs (72,954 jobs / 15,295 companies).

plt.ylabel('Count')

for i, v in enumerate([len(df),  df["company"].nunique(), (len(df) /  df["company"].nunique())*1000]):

             ha='center', va='bottom', fontweight='bold', fontsize=12)

In [87]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
avg_salary = df.groupby(["max_experience"]).agg({"min_salary":"mean","max_salary":"mean"}).round(2)
sns.lineplot(data=avg_salary, 
             linewidth=3,
             marker="D", 
             markersize=8,
             palette=['blue', 'red'],  
             markerfacecolor='green',      
             markeredgecolor='yellow',     
             markeredgewidth=2,
             linestyle=":")

plt.xlabel("Maximum Experience Required (Years)", 
           fontweight="bold", 
           fontsize=14,
           color='#1A252F') 

plt.ylabel("Average Salary (Currency Units)", 
           fontweight="bold", 
           fontsize=14,
           color='#1A252F') 

plt.title("Average Salary Distribution by Experience Level", 
          fontweight="bold", 
          fontsize=18,
          color='#1A252F', 
          pad=20)

for col_idx, column in enumerate(avg_salary.columns):
    for i, (x, y) in enumerate(zip(avg_salary.index, avg_salary[column].values)):
        if i % 3 == 0:  
            plt.annotate(f'{y:,.0f}', 
                        (x, y), 
                        textcoords="offset points", 
                        xytext=(0, 15 if col_idx == 0 else -20), 
                        ha='center',
                        fontsize=9,
                        fontweight='bold',
                        color='#2C3E50', 
                        bbox=dict(boxstyle="round,pad=0.3", 
                                facecolor='#ECF0F1', 
                                alpha=0.7,
                                edgecolor='none'))

plt.grid(True)

plt.legend(['Minimum Salary', 'Maximum Salary'], 
                   loc='upper left',
                   frameon=True,
                   fancybox=True,
                   shadow=True,
                   fontsize=12,
                   facecolor='#FDFEFE',  
                   edgecolor='#BDC3C7') 
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
